2vO"},{"type":"strong","children":[{"type":"text","value":"destroyed","key":"GRZbaz1i1T"}],"key":"K98xP2GD8U"},{"type":"text","value":". You get two simple bands (like marbles through two slits), not the wavy interference pattern.","key":"sw5xFhDW0p"}],"key":"XZ3AU3hrmq"},{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"strong","children":[{"type":"text","value":"b)","key":"dmuELqx7Jc"}],"key":"KD5rIx7Pt9"},{"type":"text","value":" No! Even an ","key":"ukn4Kqz7Xc"},{"type":"emphasis","children":[{"type":"text","value":"ideal","key":"xoeda1pJYF"}],"key":"w2VtFfb6Mj"},{"type":"text","value":" detector destroys the pattern. The act of gaining which-path information — even in principle — collapses the superposition. You cannot have definite path information ","key":"VzQ506JMf3"},{"type":"emphasis","children":[{"type":"text","value":"and","key":"kEwtxbGcmk"}],"key":"LalJXRUihP"},{"type":"text","value":" an interference pattern at the same time. This is a fundamental limit, not a technological limitation.","key":"szr3F85kiy"}],"key":"C6YEVRjLo5"},{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"strong","children":[{"type":"text","value":"c)","key":"kNYgoBVnPm"}],"key":"f6CO4g7e7B"},{"type":"text","value":" Remarkably, ","key":"sOWFlUMvOp"},{"type":"strong","children":[{"type":"text","value":"yes!","key":"xno6dWefmh"}],"key":"Y8zyH95YH7"},{"type":"text","value":" Quantum eraser experiments have confirmed this. If you arrange the experiment so that the which-path information is irreversibly erased before you examine the detector records, the interference pattern is restored. This has been demonstrated with photons in real labs. The quantum system doesn’t “know” you looked — it only responds to whether the information ","key":"BAA7ppehCr"},{"type":"emphasis","children":[{"type":"text","value":"exists","key":"mirXEPhPNG"}],"key":"vtwTfcB0QR"},{"type":"text","value":" in the universe.","key":"dpRTtuqzmK"}],"key":"uwLPuliQxk"},{"type":"heading","depth":4,"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Answer 1.5","key":"s83pUG0SLC"}],"identifier":"answer-1-5","label":"Answer 1.5","html_id":"answer-1-5","implicit":true,"key":"vZdXEUG26x"},{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"The light bulb analogy is a ","key":"oNkwR6hmP8"},{"type":"strong","children":[{"type":"text","value":"classical mixture","key":"L5OxtgQXOo"}],"key":"F0GpguIBU1"},{"type":"text","value":", not a quantum superposition. If you simply don’t know whether the bulb is on or off, the bulb is ","key":"pXoyUbXgY6"},{"type":"emphasis","children":[{"type":"text","value":"definitely","key":"YKuHkBYeSG"}],"key":"GuQZraSuWi"},{"type":"text","value":" in one state or the other — you just lack information.","key":"BchMhd4rbV"}],"key":"ol6K9nByQ3"},{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"A true quantum superposition is different: the system genuinely occupies ","key":"lAdSzx6rQu"},{"type":"emphasis","children":[{"type":"text","value":"both","key":"h6E41IVF8E"}],"key":"TJbptCB0tT"},{"type":"text","value":" states simultaneously, and the amplitudes from both states can ","key":"fbg9qYinSF"},{"type":"strong","children":[{"type":"text","value":"interfere","key":"p8nvO9K0lJ"}],"key":"bKeIQwy3VM"},{"type":"text","value":" with each other. If you had two slightly different superpositions and combined them, they could add up constructively (like ocean waves) or destructively (canceling each other out). A classical “unknown” can’t do that — either the bulb is on or it isn’t, and the probabilities just add.","key":"SONnq9rQp9"}],"key":"AZtLzOUuHA"},{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"The key test: can you observe interference? If yes, it’s a quantum superposition, not classical ignorance.","key":"UXxL9Ve7QZ"}],"key":"vYTLEInNbg"}],"key":"lyXyKO3HVd"}],"key":"z8Qgf1rJCI"}],"key":"ectFL0I2Zs"},"references":{"cite":{"order":[],"data":{}}}}